{"id": "0c405dd4ae9e4a03bba803d24cbe0fb3", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 01:16:34", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "This is a fascinating direction to pursue, especially given the growing interest in probing the compositional and logical generalization capabilities of language models. The question of whether language models can generalize monotonicity-based NPI (Negative Polarity Item) licensing—such as the use of \"any\" in downward-entailing environments—to unseen syntactic or semantic contexts without explicit training, strikes at the heart of whether these models are learning abstract linguistic principles or merely surface-level statistical patterns.\n\nMonotonicity reasoning has long been a benchmark for linguistic competence: upward-entailing contexts (e.g., \"I saw something\") license positive polarity items (\"I saw something unusual\"), while downward-entailing contexts (e.g., \"I didn’t see something\") license NPIs (\"I didn’t see anything unusual\"). Humans apply this systematically, even in novel constructions. But do language models do the same?\n\nRecent work suggests that while LMs perform well on trained instances of NPIs, they often fail under systematic generalization tests—such as new quantifiers, embeddings, or syntactic structures not seen during training (e.g., McCoy et al., 2020; Gulordava et al., 2018). This raises the possibility that their success is due to memorization rather than rule-like abstraction.\n\nWhat makes this research particularly impactful is its potential to bridge formal semantics and deep learning. By designing controlled generalization benchmarks—where models are trained on a subset of monotonicity contexts (e.g., with \"every\" and \"no\") and tested on held-out operators (e.g., \"few\", \"at most three\") or novel syntactic embeddings—we could isolate whether models are sensitive to the *monotonicity properties* of linguistic environments, rather than just associating specific words with NPIs.\n\nMoreover, we could manipulate the degree of syntactic divergence or semantic novelty in test cases to create a hierarchy of generalization difficulty. For example:\n- Can a model trained on NPIs in sentential negation (\"She doesn't have any books\") generalize to nonveridical contexts like questions or conditionals (\"Does she have any books?\")?\n- Can it handle numerically quantified downward-entailing environments it’s never seen before?\n\nWe might also explore whether certain architectural choices (e.g., encoder-decoder vs. causal LM, inclusion of syntactic supervision, chain-of-thought prompting) improve such generalization.\n\nThe broader implication is clear: if models *can* generalize NPI licensing based on monotonicity without explicit training, it would suggest an emergent capacity for abstract semantic reasoning. If not, it highlights a critical limitation—one that must be addressed for models to achieve robust, human-like language understanding.\n\nThis line of inquiry aligns well with our team’s strengths in both linguistic theory and model interpretability. It’s innovative because it moves beyond accuracy metrics to probe the *nature* of learned representations, and it has high impact potential in guiding future architectures toward genuine compositional generalization.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "024bb77fc9e6479d83f2ab35e5a81808", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 01:16:39", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "This discussion explores whether language models can generalize monotonicity-based NPI licensing (e.g., correct use of \"any\") in novel syntactic or semantic contexts, testing if models rely on abstract linguistic principles rather than surface-level patterns. While LMs perform well on familiar NPI instances, evidence shows they often fail systematic generalization—especially with unseen quantifiers or structures—suggesting reliance on memorization. The proposed research aims to design controlled benchmarks that assess generalization across a hierarchy of difficulty, such as new downward-entailing contexts (e.g., \"few\", \"at most three\") or nonveridical environments (questions, conditionals). It also considers how architecture (e.g., encoder-decoder vs. causal LM), syntactic supervision, or prompting strategies like chain-of-thought may influence performance. Success would indicate emergent abstract reasoning; failure underscores a key limitation for achieving human-like language understanding. This work bridges formal semantics and deep learning, with high potential to advance compositional generalization in models.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "6bd168f071004e2686693ffc69493158", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 01:16:39", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "[retrieved]:", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "c5c0608f3b1d42d891b0ba5c1d5893cd", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 01:16:53", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "Building on the previous discussion, I’d like to refine and deepen our focus around the core question: *Can language models truly acquire and generalize abstract semantic principles—specifically monotonicity-based licensing of negative polarity items (NPIs) like \"any\"—when faced with environments that are structurally or semantically unseen during training?*\n\nThis is not just a test of linguistic competence but a probe into whether modern LMs can perform *compositionally robust generalization*, a hallmark of human language understanding. Current evidence suggests that while models excel at surface-level pattern matching—e.g., recognizing “I don’t have any…” as acceptable—they struggle when presented with novel downward-entailing (DE) operators such as rare quantifiers (“fewer than five”), nonveridical contexts (e.g., “doubt” in embedded clauses), or complex scopal interactions.\n\nWhat makes this both challenging and promising is that NPI licensing is governed by formal semantic constraints tied to entailment direction: NPIs are licensed in DE or nonveridical contexts but prohibited in upward-entailing ones. If models were sensitive to these abstract properties—not just lexical co-occurrence statistics—they should correctly accept “Few students read any books” (DE) while rejecting “Many students read any books” (UE), even if they’ve never encountered “few” or “many” paired with “any” in training data.\n\nTo rigorously test this, we could design a hierarchical evaluation suite:\n1. **Controlled syntactic templates** with systematically varied licensors (known vs. novel DE operators).\n2. **Semantic minimal pairs** contrasting UE and DE environments using unfamiliar predicates or numerals.\n3. **Cross-linguistic probes**, leveraging languages with different NPI forms or licensing conditions, to assess universality.\n4. **Probing for abstraction**: Can models transfer knowledge from one type of DE context (e.g., negation) to another (e.g., antecedents of conditionals)?\n\nMoreover, we should investigate architectural and training factors influencing success:\n- Do encoder-decoder models (with more structured pretraining) outperform purely causal LMs?\n- Does explicit syntactic supervision (e.g., parse-aware fine-tuning) improve generalization?\n- Can chain-of-thought or explanation-based prompting elicit latent reasoning about entailment?\n\nA positive result—robust generalization to unseen DE environments—would suggest that some models may be approximating aspects of formal semantic computation. A negative result, however, would highlight a critical gap: despite fluency, LMs lack deep compositional semantics.\n\nThe broader impact lies in bridging symbolic and neural paradigms. By grounding evaluation in formal linguistic theory, we provide a high-precision tool for measuring cognitive plausibility in AI systems. This could inform next-generation models designed not just for correlation, but for abstraction.\n\nSo my proposal is to position this work as a *stress test for compositional generalization grounded in formal semantics*, using NPI licensing as a paradigmatic case. It’s innovative because it moves beyond accuracy on standard benchmarks toward diagnosing *how* models reason—or fail to reason—about meaning.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "886e832670b04e8daac4c98e4014ed0b", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 01:17:00", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "Scientist1 refines the research focus to test whether language models can generalize **abstract semantic principles**—specifically monotonicity-based licensing of NPIs like \"any\"—in **unseen syntactic or semantic contexts**, positioning this as a **stress test for compositional generalization**. The core question centers on whether models rely on deep semantic understanding (e.g., sensitivity to downward-entailing environments) or shallow pattern matching.\n\nKey proposals include:\n- Developing a **hierarchical evaluation suite** with:  \n  1) Controlled syntactic templates using known and novel DE operators,  \n  2) Semantic minimal pairs contrasting UE and DE contexts with unfamiliar elements,  \n  3) Cross-linguistic probes to assess generalization across languages,  \n  4) Transfer tests to see if knowledge from one DE context (e.g., negation) applies to others (e.g., conditionals).\n\nAdditionally, Scientist1 suggests investigating factors that may influence abstraction:\n- Model architecture (encoder-decoder vs. causal LMs),  \n- Syntactic supervision during training,  \n- Prompting methods like chain-of-thought to elicit reasoning about entailment.\n\nThe outcome has theoretical and practical implications: success would indicate emergent abstract reasoning aligned with formal semantics; failure would expose a fundamental limitation in current LMs’ compositional abilities. This approach innovatively uses **NPI licensing as a high-precision diagnostic tool** to probe cognitive plausibility and bridge symbolic linguistic theory with neural modeling.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
